Package org.freeinternals.format.png

Class Chunk_iTXt

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.freeinternals.commonlib.core.FileComponent
      • org.freeinternals.format.png.Chunk
        • org.freeinternals.format.png.Chunk_iTXt
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    org.freeinternals.commonlib.ui.GenerateTreeNode
    public class Chunk_iTXt
extends Chunk
    This chunk is semantically equivalent to the tEXt and zTXt chunks, but the textual data is in the UTF-8 encoding of the Unicode character set instead of Latin-1.

    This chunk contains: 

     Keyword:             1-79 bytes (character string)
 Null separator:      1 byte
 Compression flag:    1 byte
 Compression method:  1 byte
 Language tag:        0 or more bytes (character string)
 Null separator:      1 byte
 Translated keyword:  0 or more bytes
 Null separator:      1 byte
 Text:                0 or more bytes
    Author:
    Amos Shi
    See Also:
    Chunk_tEXt, Chunk_zTXt

      • CompressionFlag

        public final int CompressionFlag
        The compression flag is 0 for uncompressed text, 1 for compressed text. Only the text field may be compressed.

      • CompressionMethod

        public final int CompressionMethod
        The only value presently defined for the compression method byte is 0, meaning zlib data stream with deflate compression. For uncompressed text, encoders should set the compression method to 0 and decoders should ignore it.

      • LanguageTag

        public final String LanguageTag
        The language tag [RFC-1766] indicates the human language used by the translated keyword and the text. Unlike the keyword, the language tag is case-insensitive. It is an ASCII [ISO-646] string consisting of hyphen-separated words of 1-8 letters each (for example: cn, en-uk, no-bok, x-klingon). If the first word is two letters long, it is an ISO language code [ISO-639]. If the language tag is empty, the language is unspecified.

      • TranslatedKeyword

        public final byte[] TranslatedKeyword
        The translated keyword and text both use the UTF-8 encoding of the Unicode character set [ISO/IEC-10646-1], and neither may contain a zero byte (null character).
